<p>For <strong>billiards</strong> enthusiasts and those participating in <s=
trong>pool tournaments</strong>, understanding the game=E2=80=99s intricaci=
es is crucial. One such intricacy is mastering the art of aiming, which inv=
olves understanding the exact point to strike. This knowledge, often acquir=
ed through extensive practice, builds muscle memory over time. However, for=
 amateurs or those looking to understand <strong>how to play pool angles</s=
trong>, dedicating such time might not be feasible. Hence, a scientific and=
 systematic study becomes essential.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Billiard Table Draft" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholde=
r.svg" data-src=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltabl=
e3.png"></p>
<p>The image above illustrates the basic setup of a <strong>pool table</str=
ong>. The challenge is to strike the white ball (W) in such a way that the =
target ball (T) goes into the hole (H). This involves <strong>calculating a=
ngles in pool</strong>, a skill that can be daunting for beginners. But wit=
h the right <strong>pool angle calculator</strong> or <strong>pool shot cal=
culator</strong>, it becomes more manageable.</p>
<p>For those new to the game, understanding <strong>pool angles for beginne=
rs</strong> can be a game-changer. The positioning stars on the pool table,=
 often referred to as the <strong>pool table angle chart</strong>, serve as=
 reference points, helping in determining the <strong>pool ball angles</str=
ong>.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Positioning Stars" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.s=
vg" data-src=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable4.=
png"></p>
<p>The distances between these positioning stars are consistent. The long s=
ide of the billiard table has 8 segments, and the short side has 4. This un=
iformity aids in calculating the angles:</p>
<pre tabindex=3D"0"><code>=E2=88=A0glh =3D arctan(0.25) =3D 14 degrees
=E2=88=A0flh =3D arctan(0.5) =3D 27 degrees
=E2=88=A0elh =3D arctan(0.75) =3D 37 degrees
=E2=88=A0dlh =3D arctan(1) =3D 45 degrees
=E2=88=A0clh =3D arctan(1.25) =3D 51 degrees
=E2=88=A0blh =3D arctan(1.5) =3D 56 degrees
=E2=88=A0alh =3D arctan(1.75) =3D 60 degrees
=E2=88=A0olh =3D arctan(2) =3D 63 degrees
</code></pre><p>These 8 angles are enough to cover any angle change in bill=
iards, so you need to remember.</p>
<p>Now let=E2=80=99s go back to the first picture and show how to calculate=
 the angle of =E2=88=A0WTH.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable.png=
"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"ht=
tps://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable.png"></a></p>
<p>We can know by drawing an extension cord:</p>
<p>The extension point T of HT almost coincides with 37 position, so the =
=E2=88=A0O=E2=80=99HT angle is 36 degrees.</p>
<p>The extension point W=E2=80=99 of HW is almost at the 51 position, so th=
e =E2=88=A0O=E2=80=99HW angle is 53 degrees.</p>
<p>Thus the =E2=88=A0WHT angle is equal to 53-36 =3D 17 degrees.</p>
<p>We also need to draw a parallel line HH=E2=80=99 of WT.</p>
<p>H=E2=80=99 is almost a little more than two positioning stars. Compared =
with the long side, it is a little more than arctan (0.25).</p>
<p>From this, the angle of =E2=88=A0OHH=E2=80=99 is estimated to be a littl=
e more than 14. Calculated 16 degrees.</p>
<p>Then the angle of =E2=88=A0H=E2=80=99HW=3D90-16-53=3D21 degrees</p>
<p>From this, the=E2=88=A0WTH angle =3D 180-21-17 =3D 142 degrees</p>
<p>However, when we aim at it, we don=E2=80=99t need to calculate the obtus=
e angle. If we can directly calculate the acute angle, the =E2=88=A0WTT=E2=
=80=99 angle is 21+17=3D38 degrees.</p>
<p>The angle is calculated. The next question is coming:</p>
<p>How do we aim at the 38 degree angle?</p>
<p>Another picture</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable2.pn=
g"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"h=
ttps://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable2.png"></a></p>
<p>The T point is the pendulum point, the =E2=88=A0THO angle is 45 degrees,=
 and the Tab angle is arctan (2) is 63 degreee.</p>
<p>Then you can know that the angle of =E2=88=A0aTH is 63+45=3D108 degrees.=
</p>
<p>We converted it to an acute angle of 72 degrees.</p>
<p>In the same way, we calculate that point b is a 45-degree angle.</p>
<p>Point c is 63-45 =3D 18 degrees.</p>
<p>The d point is 0 degrees. No need to consider</p>
<p>The e point is 45-arctan (2/3) =3D 45-33 =3D 12 degrees</p>
<p>The point f is 45-arctan (2/4) =3D 45-27 =3D 18 degrees. Just like c, ju=
st aim from the other direction.</p>
<p>The g point is 45-arctan (2/5) =3D 45-22 =3D 23 degrees.</p>
<p>h point is 45-arctan(2/6)=3D45-18=3D27 degrees</p>
<p>The i point is 45-arctan (1/6) =3D 45-9 =3D 36 degrees</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"version-20--the-ultimate-8-ball-pool-angle-calculator">Version 2.=
0:  The Ultimate 8 Ball Pool Angle Calculator</h2>
<p>Two days after my initial post on <strong>how to get better at pool angl=
es</strong>, I realized some shortcomings in my approach:</p>
<ol>
<li>The angles calculated were based on the white ball, target ball, and th=
e target hole. Given the diameter of the ball (5-6 cm), this could lead to =
significant errors.</li>
<li>The images used for illustration had two balls, but in actual aiming, t=
he white ball isn=E2=80=99t present, making precise aiming challenging.</li=
>
</ol>
<p>This led to the introduction of version 2.0, a more refined <strong>pool=
 angles calculator</strong>.</p>
<p>Firstly, it=E2=80=99s essential to understand that the hole=E2=80=99s si=
ze is more than twice that of the ball. This means our aiming point is an a=
rea, not an exact spot.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Updated Approach" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.sv=
g" data-src=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable21.=
jpg"></p>
<p>From the image above, it=E2=80=99s evident that as long as the white bal=
l strikes the small triangular area drawn, the target ball can enter the ho=
le.</p>
<p>In addition to the long side=E2=80=99s positioning stars, the short side=
 also offers several reference points:</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Short Side Reference" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholde=
r.svg" data-src=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltabl=
e4.png"></p>
<p>Several angles caused by rearranging the short sides from small to large=
"</p>
<blockquote>
<p>=E2=88=A0iOh=3D arctan(1/8) =3D 7 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0jOh=3D arctan (2/8) =3D 14 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0kOh=3D arctan (3/8)=3D 21 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0lOh=3D arctan (4/8) =3D 27 degrees</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Several angles caused by the long side:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>=E2=88=A0glh=3D arctan (0.25)=3D 14 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0flh=3D arctan (0.5)=3D 27 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0elh=3D arctan (0.75)=3D 37 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0dlh=3D arctan(1)=3D 45 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0clh=3D arctan(1.25)=3D 51 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0blh=3D arctan (1.5)=3D 56 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0alh=3D arctan(1.75)=3D 60 degrees</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0olh=3D arctan (2)=3D 63 degrees
The next challenge is to quickly calculate these angles:</p>
</blockquote>
<p><img alt=3D"Angle Calculation" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.s=
vg" data-src=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable20=
.jpg"></p>
<p>This version focuses on the angle =E2=88=A0WTT, which involves a virtual=
 white ball (T). In practice, you can align the cue stick along the target =
ball and the target hole, then determine the position of T.</p>
<p>In reality, you can take the rod along the target ball and the target ho=
le, then get T =E2=80=9Cin which positioning star.</p>
<p>Visually check T =E2=80=9Cpoints in the long-side =E2=80=9C37=E2=80=9D p=
osition, then</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0O=E2=80=99HT=3D 36 degrees</p>
<p>Take the rod along the target hole and draw a parallel line H=E2=80=99H =
with the WT line.</p>
<p>H=E2=80=9D point on the short side of =E2=80=9C14=E2=80=9D position, the=
n</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0OHH=E2=80=9D =3D 14 degrees</p>
<p>Then we have to calculate the angle:</p>
<p>=E2=88=A0WTT"=3D 90-36-14 =3D 40 degrees</p>
<p>A slight difference from the 38 degrees calculated in version 1.0.</p>
<p>Ok, there is no problem with the calculation angle. Now let=E2=80=99s re=
take the angle of each star in the picture below.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable2.pn=
g"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"h=
ttps://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/pooltable2.png"></a></p>
<p>Version 1.0 has calculated the sharp angles of the points and defects fo=
r each point:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The a point is 72 degrees.</p>
<p>The b point is 45 degrees.</p>
<p>The c point is 63-45 =3D 18 degrees.</p>
<p>The d point is 0 degrees. No need to consider</p>
<p>The e point is 45-arctan (2/3) =3D 45-33 =3D 12 degrees</p>
<p>The point f is 45-arctan (2/4) =3D 45-27 =3D 18 degrees. Just like c, ju=
st aim from the other direction.</p>
<p>The g point is 45-arctan (2/5) =3D 45-22 =3D 23 degrees.</p>
<p>h point is 45-arctan(2/6)=3D45-18=3D27 degrees</p>
<p>The i point is 45-arctan (1/6) =3D 45-9 =3D 36 degrees</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This time we need to put the white ball on the pendulum point and the bl=
ack ball on the HT line, so that we can enter the hole by aiming at the bal=
l.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2071935436.jp=
g"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"h=
ttps://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2071935436.jpg"></a></p>
<p>Take real photos from each point:</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/272.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/272.jpg"></a></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/245.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/245.jpg"></a></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/218.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/218.jpg"></a></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/212.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/212.jpg"></a></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/223.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/223.jpg"></a></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/227.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/227.jpg"></a></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/236.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/236.jpg"></a></p>
<p>This time, I will add a picture of about 60 degrees, because I jumped fr=
om 45 degrees to 72 degrees, and there is no more degrees in the middle.</p=
>
<p><a href=3D"https://jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/260.jpg"><img=
 alt=3D"" src=3D"https://jesselau.com/placeholder.svg" data-src=3D"https://=
jesselau.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/260.jpg"></a>
With this updated approach, I hope to provide a more accurate and practical=
 guide to mastering billiard angles. If you have suggestions or feedback, p=
lease share in the comments!</p>

